### Communication Vlog Activities and Presentation Experience

This week started with an unexpected situation in our Communication Skills class. Previously, many students, including me, misunderstood the instructions for the speaking activity because we could not attend one of the earlier classes. We received incomplete information from our friends and thought that we only had to record a simple video while standing at one place and speaking on any random topic.

However, when we came to the class with our videos, the teacher rejected them and explained that the activity was actually supposed to be a proper vlog. According to the instructions:

- The vlog should include movement and visiting different places  
- Students should explain surroundings while walking and speaking in English  
- The video should look like a real vlog experience instead of a static speech  

The teacher understood that the misunderstanding happened because many students had missed the previous class, so she gave everyone one more chance to prepare a proper vlog for evaluation.

For the next class, I created a vlog based on my hostel and university environment. My friend handled the camera while I explained different locations around Al-Biruni Hall in English. During the vlog, I visited different areas and described the surroundings while continuously speaking in front of the camera.

When we came for evaluation, the classroom environment became very interesting because:

- The classroom lights were turned off  
- Windows and doors were closed  
- Videos were displayed on the projector  
- Speakers were arranged so everyone could clearly hear the audio  

All students watched each other’s vlogs together in the classroom.

At the end of the evaluation, I received:

- **8 out of 10 marks** in the vlog activity  

The teacher also assigned another communication activity for the next class in which every student would become a teacher for 10 minutes and explain a topic in front of the entire class. Other students would ask questions, and we would have to answer them confidently.

These activities helped improve:

- Public speaking confidence  
- Camera communication skills  
- English fluency  
- Presentation abilities  
- Confidence while speaking in front of an audience  

### DLD Open-Ended Lab, OOP Activities, and Academic Responsibilities

At the same time, our Digital Logic Design open-ended lab also created a challenging academic situation.

Before the lab, our teacher instructed us to:

- Revise K-map concepts  
- Learn IC numbers and pin diagrams  
- Practice breadboard implementation  
- Understand logic circuit design  

Because of these instructions, many students thought the evaluation would mainly focus on IC memorization and theoretical concepts.

However, when we entered the lab, the teacher gave us a completely real-world scenario-based problem. We had to design a system based on conditions such as:

- High temperature  
- Vibration  
- Emergency conditions  
- Sound detection  

The task required us to:

1. Identify inputs and outputs  
2. Create the Boolean function using K-map  
3. Draw the logic diagram  
4. Implement the circuit practically on a breadboard  

Initially, many students became confused because the problem looked difficult. But after carefully understanding the scenario, I identified the variables properly and solved the truth table using variable names such as:

- E for Emergency  
- V for Vibration  
- Other variables for remaining conditions  

Since there were four variables, the combinations became 16 states in the truth table.

Alhamdulillah, I successfully solved the problem, performed well in the viva, and our breadboard implementation worked correctly. The teacher checked our inputs and outputs and appreciated the proper implementation.

During the same week, our Object-Oriented Programming activities also continued. Our previously assigned University Admission Management System project was submitted before the deadline.

Later, our lab teacher assigned a new mini project in which we had to:

- Design a 2D game in C#  
- Use the .NET Framework  
- Without Framework
- Avoid advanced game frameworks  
- Complete the project before 16 June  

In the same lab session, we also attempted quizzes and an open-ended lab based on:

- Inheritance  
- Polymorphism  
- Abstract classes  
- Object creation in C#  

The task included designing an abstract class named `Product` and creating derived classes such as:

- Clothing  
- Electronics  

We also had to create objects and display functionality properly in the main class.

Along with these activities, our DLD teacher announced results of quizzes and midterms:

- **9.5 out of 10** in quiz  
- **25 out of 30** in midterm examination  

The teacher also announced another upcoming quiz from Chapter 4.

During this same period, the university administration announced that classes would temporarily shift online from 20 May because of upcoming Eid-ul-Adha vacations. We attended online classes on 21st, 22nd, and 23rd May, while holidays continued afterwards until the university reopened physically on 1st June.

Because of the sudden schedule change, we quickly packed our luggage after the OOP lab ended and travelled to the railway station using the university route bus. Later, I travelled home and attended my online classes from there the next morning.

### Database Project Finalization, SQL Quiz, and Practical Learning

This week was also very important for our Database Systems subject because our group finally confirmed and finalized the dataset for our project.

After previous discussions and dataset rejection, we selected the **Framingham Heart Study dataset**, which is a real-world medical dataset related to heart disease prediction.

The dataset contains:

- More than 4,000 patient records  
- Multiple medical attributes  
- A target variable named `TenYearCHD`  

The target variable predicts whether a patient may develop coronary heart disease within the next ten years.

While discussing the dataset, we also learned important Machine Learning concepts such as:

- Binary classification  
- Class imbalance  
- Missing value handling  
- Importance of recall in medical predictions  
- Feature relationships in datasets  

Our teacher appreciated the dataset because:

- It was a real dataset instead of artificial data  
- It contained meaningful prediction possibilities  
- It could later be used for Machine Learning implementation  

At the same time, our teacher announced a Database quiz covering:

- Projection  
- Selection  
- Rename  
- Union  
- Intersection  
- Difference  
- Division  
- Joins and their types  
- SQL queries  

The quiz was surprisingly enjoyable because the questions were based on realistic scenarios instead of random theoretical statements.

One question contained:

- Current Account table  
- Saving Account table  

We had to:

- Find common customers  
- Find customers existing in only one account  
- Write relational algebra queries  
- Write SQL queries  
- Draw output tables  

For solving these problems, we used concepts such as:

- Union  
- Difference  
- Intersection  

Another question involved:

- Student table  
- Course table  
- Enrollment table  

We had to retrieve student and course information using SQL joins and relational algebra operations.

Because the quiz focused on practical understanding, it felt easier and more interesting to attempt.

Along with academics, university life also included enjoyable moments. On 19 May 2026, a Mela festival was organized at the university where students arranged different stalls including:

- Golgappa stalls  
- Ludo games  
- Artificial jewelry  
- Food and entertainment activities  

On the same morning, I accidentally dropped my mobile phone, and its panel came out. Later, me and my friend Tahir travelled to Khurrianwala to repair the phone, which also became a memorable experience during this busy academic week.

Overall, this week improved my:

- Technical understanding  
- Communication abilities  
- Presentation confidence  
- Practical implementation skills  
- Problem-solving abilities  
- Time management during academic pressure  ---
